</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uayllrik.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ayllrik</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 80<br> <font color=#E9D756>(11/23/01 5:18 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=41.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: wel</span><hr size=1> Basically, the anti-camping code is that the longer a mob is around, the more xp he is worth.  If you kill a mob in a given area as soon as it spawns, it's worth Y xp.  If the mob sits around for 30 minutes, it becomes worth Y+Z xp, where Z is a camp bonus.  This is to encourage you to move around so as to maximize xp gain.  But that rarely happens.<br>
<br>
Loot is just a random thing for all mobs of a given area.  That's why websites list items as dropping from a zone or particular type of creature, instead of a specific mobs.  Except, of course, the one-time only drops.  Certain specific mobs have an item that will only drop once per character.  Once you get this item, it will no longer drop for you. <p>Ayllrik<BR>
51st season über-monk supreme<BR>
