 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ukanya.showPublicProfile?language=EN>kanya</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 99<br> <font color=#E9D756>(11/23/01 12:21 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=41.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> sorta</span><hr size=1> i think mythic tried (whether or not they accomplish has yet to be seen) to corner both coop and comp in daoc.<br>
<br>
by creating a game where all people within a realm benefit their realm the most by working together against other realms supposedly doing the same thing...they get both sides.  <br>
<br>
in albion we started out with distinct guild lines.  we allied with ice upon guild creation, but i'm unsure if there were any other allied coops at all in our realm other than that.  after our first grand scale rvr experience against mid, it became immediately apparent that this would not work.  the alliance was recreated to contain most of the other high level rvring guilds to keep coms up and help each other attain the necessary levels.  i'm currently allied with a guild that (in general) i can't stand in terms of personality, but they are damn good and reliable in rvr.  for the realm, that's more important than whether or not i like them as individuals.  this game forces you to see past that and learn to cooperate with others to acheive your goals.<br>
<br>
we'll see how well it works out later when more people are spending all their time in frontiers rather than leveling to get to rvr levels.  <br>
<br>
in terms of why they have levels at all...well, most of the time mythic's response to such questions is to promote unity inside the realm.  you have to help each other all the way along the way.  also, since daoc provides you with character templates to follow (as opposed to uo's create your own), leveling allows you to learn your character and allows others who play with you to learn your capabilities and what you do.  going out to rvr when you don't know what you are capable of, or what others can do...well...  it also adds the dimension of personal power, which..as eq taught us...is very essential for some people to enjoy a game.  in the beginning, we had a guild that decided it would be the highest level guild in our realm the fastest.  they didn't succeed, exactly, but hey, it motivated them.<br>
<br>
bottom line, they wanted to create variety within their game, or they would simply have a remake of things that already existed in totality.  naturally, this won't appeal to everyone, but hey, that doesn't mean they are wrong or messed up...look how many of us don't like everquest, but they certainly have a loyal following.<br>
<br>
sorry kizmet, just caught my attention with the whole coop vs comp thing.<br>
<br>
but we have the same problem in albion.  people flock to the high level dungeons and they are pretty much always full now.  i don't hunt there because they aren't itemized, and the exp diminish happens to fast with fading bonus.  although the gold we pull out of dungeons is nice.  hehe.<br>
<br>
i'm pretty sure the highest levels in our realm still hunt in frontiers and rotate spawns a lot.  plus, that's where we gotta be to keep an eye out for those pesky mids.<br>
<br>
